Llama Guard's design is a *taxonomy classifier* run on both sides of the model. Building a mock shows the symmetric input/output guarding and the per-category output that makes it actionable.

```python
HAZARD_TAXONOMY = {       # abstract subset of the MLCommons 14-category set
    'S1': 'violent crimes', 'S9': 'indiscriminate weapons',
    'S14': 'code interpreter abuse',
}

def llama_guard_classify(content, role):
    # mock: maps benign placeholder triggers to categories; real LG uses a fine-tuned LLM
    triggers = {'cat_S1': 'S1', 'cat_S9': 'S9', 'cat_S14': 'S14'}
    for trig, cat in triggers.items():
        if trig in content:
            return {'safe': False, 'category': cat, 'role': role, 'hazard': HAZARD_TAXONOMY[cat]}
    return {'safe': True, 'category': None, 'role': role}

# guard the INPUT (user request) and the OUTPUT (model generation)
print('input  :', llama_guard_classify('benign request', 'input'))
print('input  :', llama_guard_classify('request cat_S9', 'input'))
print('output :', llama_guard_classify('generation cat_S14', 'output'))
```

Output:

```
input  : {'safe': True, 'category': None, 'role': 'input'}
input  : {'safe': False, 'category': 'S9', 'role': 'input', 'hazard': 'indiscriminate weapons'}
output : {'safe': False, 'category': 'S14', 'role': 'output', 'hazard': 'code interpreter abuse'}
```

**Why taxonomy + both-sides.** Returning the *violated category* (not just "unsafe") makes the classifier actionable — you can route different hazards to different responses, measure which hazards appear in traffic, and tune per-category thresholds. Running the *same classifier on both input and output* catches two distinct failures: a harmful *request* (input side, refuse before the model runs) and a harmful *generation* even from an innocent prompt (output side). Llama Guard 3 covers 14 MLCommons hazards plus Code Interpreter Abuse across 8 languages; Llama Guard 4 adds multimodal (image+text). The S14 (Code Interpreter Abuse) category matters specifically for agentic systems that execute generated code (Phase 17). This is the inference-time guardrail layer; the final exercise assembles the full defense-in-depth stack.
